How Networking Works â€” Layer by Layer (OSI Model)
Networking follows the OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model â€” a 7-layer conceptual model describing how data moves from a sender to a receiver.

1. Application Layer
Purpose: Provides network services to user applications.
Sender Side: Converts user data (like an email, web page request) into messages.
Receiver Side: Receives the message and displays to user.

Protocols:
HTTP/HTTPS â†’ Web browsing
SMTP, POP3, IMAP â†’ Email
DNS â†’ Domain name resolution
FTP, SFTP â†’ File transfer
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Presentation Layer
Purpose: Formats, encrypts, and compresses data before sending.
Sender Side: Converts data into a format suitable for transmission (e.g., encryption, JPEG, MP4, SSL).
Receiver Side: Decrypts, decompresses, and formats it back.
Protocols: SSL/TLS, MIME, JPEG, MP3, MPEG
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Session Layer
Purpose: Manages sessions or connections between applications.
Sender Side: Establishes and maintains the connection.
Receiver Side: Terminates the connection after communication.
Protocols: NetBIOS, RPC, PPTP
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Transport Layer
Purpose: Provides end-to-end communication, reliability, and segmentation.
Sender Side: Breaks data into segments and adds headers with source/destination ports.
Receiver Side: Reassembles data and ensures reliability.
Protocols:
TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) â€“ Reliable, ordered (e.g., web, email)
UDP (User Datagram Protocol) â€“ Fast, no guarantee (e.g., video streaming, DNS)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5.Network Layer
Purpose: Determines the best path for data (routing).
Sender Side: Adds logical addresses (IP addresses) and creates packets.
Receiver Side: Uses IP to deliver packets to correct destination.
Protocols: IP (IPv4/IPv6), ICMP, ARP, RIP, OSPF, BGP
Devices: Router
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. Data Link Layer
Purpose: Transfers data between directly connected nodes.
Sender Side: Adds MAC addresses, frames the packets.
Receiver Side: Uses MAC to identify the device and passes the frame to upper layers.
Protocols: Ethernet, PPP, HDLC, Frame Relay
Devices: Switch, Bridge
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. Physical Layer
Purpose: Transmits raw bits (0s and 1s) over physical media.
Sender Side: Converts frames into signals.
Receiver Side: Converts signals back to bits.
Protocols: Ethernet (physical part), RS-232, DSL, Wi-Fi (802.11)
Devices: Hub, Repeater, Cables, NIC
---------------------------------------
1. Application Layer
Purpose: Provides network services to user applications.
Sender Side: Converts user data (like email, web page request) into messages for transport.
Receiver Side: Receives messages and displays to the user.

Protocols:
HTTP/HTTPS â†’ Web browsing
SMTP, POP3, IMAP â†’ Email
DNS â†’ Domain name resolution
FTP, SFTP â†’ File transfer
Telnet, SSH â†’ Remote login
--------------------------------------------------------
2. Transport Layer
Purpose: Provides end-to-end communication, reliability, and segmentation.
Sender Side: Breaks data into segments and adds headers with source/destination ports.
Receiver Side: Reassembles data and ensures reliability.

Protocols:
TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) â€“ Reliable, ordered (e.g., web, email)
UDP (User Datagram Protocol) â€“ Fast, no guarantee (e.g., video streaming, DNS)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Internet Layer
Purpose: Determines logical addressing and best path for data delivery (routing).
Sender Side: Adds logical addresses (IP addresses) and encapsulates data into packets.
Receiver Side: Uses IP to deliver packets to correct destination.

Protocols:
IP (IPv4/IPv6) â†’ Addressing and routing
ICMP â†’ Error and diagnostic messages (ping, traceroute)
ARP â†’ Maps IP addresses to MAC addresses
Routing protocols: RIP, OSPF, BGP

Devices: Router
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Network Access / Link Layer
Purpose: Handles the physical transmission and data delivery between directly connected nodes.
Sender Side: Converts packets into frames, adds MAC addresses, and signals for transmission.
Receiver Side: Extracts frames, uses MAC to identify the device, and passes data to upper layers.

Protocols:
Ethernet, PPP, HDLC, Frame Relay, Wi-Fi (802.11)

Devices: Switch, Bridge, Hub, Repeater, NIC

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Networking Devices and Their Uses
Device            OSI Layer            Function
Hub               Physical             Broadcasts signals to all  devices
Switch            Data Link            Connects devices within LAN using MAC addresses
Router            Network.             Connects different networks using IP
Bridge            Data Link            Divides large LAN into smaller segments
Gateway           All layers           Connects different network architectures
Repeater          Physical             Boosts weak signals
Access Point      Data Link            Connects wireless devices to a wired network
Firewall          Network/Transport    Controls incoming and outgoing traffic

------------------------------------
IP Address Structure
IPv4 Address:
32 bits = 4 octets (e.g., 192.168.1.10)

Divided into:
Network ID: Identifies the network/subnet
Host ID: Identifies the device (host) in that network

Example:
For 192.168.1.10/24
Network ID â†’ 192.168.1.0
Host ID â†’ .10
Subnet mask â†’ 255.255.255.0
All hosts in same subnet share same network ID, but unique host IDs.

IPv6 Address:
128 bits = 16 bytes (e.g., 2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334)

Divided into:
Network Prefix: Identifies the network/subnet (similar to Network ID in IPv4)
Interface ID: Identifies the device (host) in that network

Example:
For 2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334/64
Network Prefix â†’ 2001:0db8:85a3:0000::/64
Interface ID â†’ ::8a2e:0370:7334
Prefix length â†’ /64 (similar to subnet mask in IPv4, indicates first 64 bits for network)

Notes:
IPv6 uses hexadecimal notation separated by colons.
Leading zeros in a block can be omitted (e.g., 0370 â†’ 370).
Consecutive blocks of zeros can be compressed using :: (only once per address).
