Encapsulation Process (Sender Side)
Each layer adds its own header before passing data to the next layer:

Layer        Unit        Example Header
Application        Data        HTTP Header
Transport        Segment        TCP/UDP Header (Port numbers)
Network        Packet        IP Header (Source & Destination IP)
Data Link        Frame        MAC Header (Source & Destination MAC)
Physical        Bits        Electrical / Optical signals
ğŸ” Decapsulation Process (Receiver Side)
The reverse process â€” each layer removes its header and passes the remaining data up the stack until the application receives the original.       
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Below are the topics required for networking:
1. Network Topologies
Purpose: Defines how devices are physically or logically connected.

Topology	                Description	                                        
Bus	                     Single backbone cable	                                          
Star	                    All nodes connect to central hub/switch	            
Ring	                    Nodes connected in a circular path	Equal access, no collisions	
Mesh	                    Every node connects to every other node	High redundancy, reliable	Expensive, complex
Hybrid	                  Combination of topologies	Flexible	Can be complex to design

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Subnetting (Deep)
Purpose: Divides a network into smaller logical subnets.
IPv4 Example:
IP: 192.168.10.0/24
Subnet mask: 255.255.255.0

Number of subnets formula: 2â¿ (n = number of borrowed bits)
Number of hosts formula: 2Ê° â€“ 2 (h = host bits)

Steps:
Determine subnet mask or prefix.
Calculate number of subnets and hosts per subnet.
Assign subnet IDs and host ranges.
IPv6 Subnetting: Uses prefix lengths (commonly /64). Each subnet can support 2â¶â´ hosts.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing)
Replaces traditional classful addressing.

Uses prefix notation: IP/prefix (e.g., 192.168.1.0/24).
Efficient IP allocation, reduces wasted addresses.

Example:
/24 â†’ 256 addresses
/26 â†’ 64 addresses
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. NAT Types
Purpose: Maps private IP addresses to public IPs for internet access.
NAT Type	Description
Static NAT	One-to-one mapping between private and public IP
Dynamic NAT	Private IPs mapped to pool of public IPs
PAT (NAT Overload)	Multiple private IPs use a single public IP with different ports
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. VLAN & STP
VLAN (Virtual LAN): Segments a physical network into logical networks.
Reduces broadcast domains, improves security.
STP (Spanning Tree Protocol): Prevents loops in Ethernet networks.
Blocks redundant paths and ensures one active path.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. ARP, DHCP, DNS Working

ARP (Address Resolution Protocol): Maps IP â†’ MAC on local network.
DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol): Assigns IP, subnet mask, gateway dynamically.
DNS (Domain Name System): Resolves domain names â†’ IP addresses.

Flow Example (DHCP):
DHCP Discover â†’ broadcast
DHCP Offer â†’ server response
DHCP Request â†’ client accepts
DHCP ACK â†’ server confirms
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. TCP 3-Way Handshake & 4-Way Termination
3-Way Handshake (Connection Establishment):
SYN â†’ Client requests connection
SYN-ACK â†’ Server acknowledges
ACK â†’ Client confirms

4-Way Termination (Connection Close):
FIN â†’ Initiator closes
ACK â†’ Receiver acknowledges
FIN â†’ Receiver closes
ACK â†’ Initiator acknowledges
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. Routing Types
Static Routing: Manually configured routes.
Dynamic Routing: Routes learned automatically via protocols (RIP, OSPF, BGP).
Default Route: Route used if no specific match is found.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
9. Switching Process
Switch learns MAC addresses â†’ builds MAC table.
Frames are forwarded based on destination MAC.
Floods unknown destinations to all ports.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
10. OSI vs TCP/IP
OSI Layer	TCP/IP Layer	Key Function
Application	Application	Network services to apps
Presentation	Application	Formatting, encryption
Session	Application	Connection management
Transport	Transport	End-to-end delivery (TCP/UDP)
Network	Internet	Logical addressing, routing
Data Link	Network Access	Frames, MAC addresses
Physical	Network Access	Raw bit transmission
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
11. MTU & Fragmentation

MTU (Maximum Transmission Unit): Largest packet size a network can handle.
Fragmentation: Splits packets exceeding MTU.
IPv4: Routers can fragment.
IPv6: Hosts must fragment; routers do not.
---------------------------------------------------------------
12. Broadcast / Multicast / Unicast
Type	Description
Unicast	One-to-one
Broadcast	One-to-all on subnet
Multicast	One-to-many (specific group)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
13. Network Security Basics
Firewalls: Filter traffic
IDS/IPS: Detect/prevent attacks
VPN: Secure remote access
Encryption: Protects data integrity and confidentiality
----------------------------------------------------------------------
14. Additional Devices
Device	Function
Hub	Simple repeater, no filtering
Switch	MAC-based frame forwarding
Router	IP-based packet routing
Bridge	Connects 2 LANs
Access Point	Wireless network access
Repeater	Extends signal
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
15. End-to-End Data Flow Summary
Application generates data â†’ TCP/UDP segments
TCP/UDP adds headers â†’ hands to IP
IP adds source/destination addresses â†’ packet
Data Link adds MAC addresses â†’ frame
Physical layer converts to signals â†’ sent over medium
Receiver reverses steps â†’ data delivered to application
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------



